###### Abstract

This work presents ReSync, a Riemannian subgradient-based algorithm for solving the robust rotation synchronization problem, which arises in various engineering applications. ReSync solves a least-unsquared minimization formulation over the rotation group, which is nonsmooth and nonconvex, and aims at recovering the underlying rotations directly. We provide strong theoretical guarantees for ReSync under the random corruption setting. Specifically, we first show that the initialization procedure of ReSync yields a proper initial point that lies in a local region around the ground-truth rotations. We next establish the weak sharpness property of the aforementioned formulation and then utilize this property to derive the local linear convergence of ReSync to the ground-truth rotations. By combining these guarantees, we conclude that ReSync converges linearly to the ground-truth rotations under appropriate conditions. Experiment results demonstrate the effectiveness of ReSync.

## 1 Introduction

Rotation synchronization (RS) is a fundamental problem in many engineering applications. For instance, RS (also known as "rotation averaging") is an important subproblem of structure from motion (SfM) and simultaneous localization and mapping (SLAM) in computer vision [20, 22, 17], where the goal is to compute the absolute orientations of objects from relative rotations between pairs of objects. RS has also been applied to sensor network localization [41, 12], signal recovery from phaseless observations [2], digital communications [36], and cryo-EM imaging [35, 33].

Practical measurements of relative rotations are often _incomplete_ and _corrupted_, leading to the problem of robust rotation synchronization (RRS) [28, 21, 22, 39, 9, 31]. The goal of RRS is to reconstruct a set of ground-truth rotations \(\bm{X}_{1}^{\star},\cdots,\bm{X}_{i}^{\star},\cdots,\bm{X}_{n}^{\star}\in \mathrm{SO}(d)\) from measurements ofrelative rotations represented as

\[\mathbf{Y}_{ij}=\begin{cases}\mathbf{X}_{i}^{\star}\mathbf{X}_{j}^{\star\top},&(i, j)\in\mathcal{A},\\ \mathbf{O}_{ij},&(i,j)\in\mathcal{E}\setminus\mathcal{A},\\ \mathbf{0},&(i,j)\in\mathcal{E}^{c},\end{cases}\quad\text{with}\quad(i,j)\in \begin{cases}\mathcal{A},&\text{with ratio }pq,\\ \mathcal{E}\setminus\mathcal{A},&\text{with ratio }(1-p)q,\\ \mathcal{E}^{c},&\text{otherwise}.\end{cases}\] (1)

Here, \(\mathrm{SO}(d):=\big{\{}\bm{R}\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times d}:\bm{R}^{\top}\bm{R}= \bm{I},\mathrm{det}(\bm{R})=1\big{\}}\) denotes the rotation group (also known as the special orthogonal group), \(\mathcal{E}\) represents the indices of all available observations, \(\mathcal{A}\) denotes the indices of true observations, \(\mathcal{A}^{c}:=\mathcal{E}\setminus\mathcal{A}\) is the indices of _outliers_, \(\bm{O}_{ij}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)\) is an outlying observation, and the missing observations are set to be \(\bm{0}\) by convention; see, e.g., [23, section 2.1]. We use \(q\in(0,1)\) to denote the observation ratio and \(p\in(0,1)\) to denote the ratio of true observations.

**Related works.** Due to the vast amount of research in this field, our overview will necessarily focus on theoretical investigations of \(\mathsf{RS}\). In the case where no outliers exist in the measurement model (1), i.e., \(p=1\), a natural formulation is to minimize a smooth least-squares function \(\sum_{(j,j)\in\mathcal{E}}\|\bm{X}_{i}\bm{X}_{j}^{\top}-\bm{Y}_{ij}\|_{F}^{2}\) over \(\bm{X}_{i}\in\mathrm{SO}(d),\;1\leq i\leq n\). Spectral relaxation and semidefinite relaxation (SDR) are typical approaches for addressing this problem [34, 3, 6, 5, 4, 30], where they provide strong recovery guarantees. However, these results cannot be directly applied to the corrupted model (1) due to the existence of outliers (i.e., \(p<1\)) and the sensitivity of the least-squares solution to outlying observations.

Theoretical understanding of \(\mathsf{RRS}\) is still rather limited. One typical setting for theoretical analysis of \(\mathsf{RRS}\) is the random corruption model (\(\mathsf{RCM}\)); see Section 2.2. The work [39] introduces a least-unsquared formulation and applies the SDR method to tackle it. Under the \(\mathsf{RCM}\) and in the full observation case where \(q=1\), it is shown that the minimizer of the SDR reformulation exactly recovers the underlying Gram matrix (hence the ground-truth rotations) under the conditions that the true observation ratio \(p\geq 0.46\) for \(\mathrm{SO}(2)\) (and \(p\geq 0.49\) for \(\mathrm{SO}(3)\)) and \(n\to\infty\). In [23], the authors established the relationship between cycle-consistency and exact recovery and introduced a message-passing algorithm. Their method is tailored to find the corruption level in the graph, rather than recovering the ground-truth rotations directly. They provided linear convergence guarantees for their algorithm once the ratios satisfy \(p^{8}q^{2}=\Omega(\log n/n)\) under the \(\mathsf{RCM}\). However, it is unclear how this message-passing algorithm is related to other optimization procedures for solving the problem. Let us mention that they also provided guarantees for other compact groups and corruption settings. Following partly the framework established in [23], the work [32] presents an interesting nonconvex quadratic programming formulation of \(\mathsf{RRS}\). It is shown that the global minimizer of the nonconvex formulation recovers the true corruption level (still not the ground-true rotations directly) when \(p^{2}q^{2}=\Omega(\log n/n)\) under the \(\mathsf{RCM}\). Unfortunately, the work does not provide a concrete algorithm that provably finds a global minimizer of the nonconvex formulation. In [29], the authors introduced and analyzed a depth descent algorithm for recovering the underlying rotation matrices. In the context of the \(\mathsf{RCM}\), they showed asymptotic convergence of their algorithm to the underlying rotations without providing a specific rate. The result is achieved under the conditions that the algorithm is initialized near \(\bm{X}^{\star}\), \(q\geq\mathcal{O}(\log n/n)\), and \(p\geq 1-1/(d(d-1)+2)\). The latter requirement translates to \(p\geq 3/4\) for \(\mathrm{SO}(2)\) and \(p\geq 7/8\) for \(\mathrm{SO}(3)\). It is important to note, however, that the primary focus of their research lies in the adversarial corruption setup rather than the \(\mathsf{RCM}\).

**Main contributions.** Towards tackling the \(\mathsf{RRS}\) problem under the measurement model (1), we consider the following least-unsquared formulation, which was introduced in [39] as the initial step for applying the SDR method:

\[\begin{split}&\underset{\bm{X}\in\mathbb{R}^{nd\times d}}{\text{ minimize}}\;f(\bm{X}):=\sum_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{E}}\|\bm{X}_{i}\bm{X}_{j}^{\top}-\bm{Y}_{ij} \|_{F}\\ &\mathrm{subject\;to}\;\bm{X}_{i}\in\mathrm{SO}(d),\;1\leq i\leq n.\end{split}\] (2)

Note that this problem is _nonsmooth_ and _nonconvex_ due to the unsquared Frobenius-norm loss and the rotation group constraint, respectively. We design a _Riemannian **S**ubgradient **s**ynchronization algorithm (\(\mathsf{ReSync}\)) for addressing problem (2); see Algorithm 1. \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) will first call an initialization procedure named \(\mathsf{Spectrin}\) (see Algorithm 2), which is a spectral relaxation method. Then, it implements an iterative Riemannian subgradient procedure. \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) targets at directly recovering the ground-truth rotations \(\bm{X}^{\star}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}\) rather than the Gram matrix or the corruption level. Under the \(\mathsf{RCM}\) (see Section 2.2), we provide the following strong theoretical guarantees for \(\mathsf{ReSync}\):1. _Initialization_. The first step of \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) is to call \(\mathsf{SpectrIn}\) for computing the initial point \(\bm{X}^{0}\). Theoretically, we establish that \(\bm{X}^{0}\) can be relatively close to \(\bm{X}^{\star}\) depending on \(p\) and \(q\); see Theorem 2.
2. _Weak sharpness_. We then establish a problem-intrinsic property of the formulation (2) called weak sharpness; see Theorem 3. This property characterizes the geometry of problem (2) and is of independent interest.
3. _Convergence analysis_. Finally, we derive the local linear rate of convergence for \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) based on the established weak sharpness property; see Theorem 4.

The main idea is that the weak sharpness property in (S.2) helps to show _linear convergence_ of \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) to \(\bm{X}^{\star}\) in (S.3). However, this result only holds _locally_. Thus, we need the initialization guarantee in (S.1) to initialize our algorithm in this local region and then argue that it will not leave this region once initialized. We refer to Sections 3.1 to 3.3 for more technical challenges and our proof ideas. Combining the above theoretical results yields our overall guarantee: \(\mathsf{ReSync}\)_converges linearly to the ground-truth rotations \(\bm{X}^{\star}\) when \(p^{7}q^{2}=\Omega(\log n/n)\)_; see Theorem 1.

**Notation**. Our notation is mostly standard. We use \(\mathbb{R}^{nd\times d}\ni\bm{X}=(\bm{X}_{1};\ldots;\bm{X}_{n})\in\mathrm{SO}(d) ^{n}\) to represent the Cartesian product of all the variables \(\bm{X}_{i}\in\mathrm{SO}(d),1\leq i\leq n\). The same applies to the ground-truth rotations \(\bm{X}^{\star}=(\bm{X}_{1}^{\star};\cdots;\bm{X}_{n}^{\star})\). Let \(\mathcal{E}_{i}=\{j\mid(i,j)\in\mathcal{E}\}\), \(\mathcal{A}_{i}=\{j\mid(i,j)\in\mathcal{A}\}\), and \(\mathcal{A}_{i}^{c}=\mathcal{E}_{i}\setminus\mathcal{A}_{i}\). We also define \(\mathcal{A}_{ij}=\mathcal{A}_{i}\cap\mathcal{A}_{j}\) for simplicity. For a set \(S\), we use \(|S|\) to denote its cardinality. For any matrix \(\bm{X},\bm{Y}\in\mathbb{R}^{nd\times d}\), we define the following distance up to a global rotation:

\[\mathrm{dist}\left(\bm{X},\bm{Y}\right)=\|\bm{X}-\bm{Y}\bm{R}^{\star}\|_{F}, \text{ where }\bm{R}^{\star}=\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{\bm{R}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)}\|\bm{X} \bm{R}-\bm{Y}\|_{F}^{2}=\mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{SO}(d)}(\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{Y}).\]

Besides, we introduce the following distances up to the global rotation \(\bm{R}^{\star}\) defined above:

\[\mathrm{dist}_{1}\left(\bm{X},\bm{Y}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm{Y} _{i}\bm{R}^{\star}\|_{F},\quad\mathrm{dist}_{\infty}\left(\bm{X},\bm{Y}\right) =\max_{1\leq i\leq n}\|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm{Y}_{i}\bm{R}^{\star}\|_{F}.\]

## 2 Algorithm and Setup

### ReSync: Algorithm Development

In this subsection, we present \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) for tackling the nonsmooth nonconvex formulation (2); see Algorithm 1. Our algorithm has two main parts, i.e., initialization and an iterative Riemannian subgradient procedure.

**Initialization.**\(\mathsf{ReSync}\) first calls a procedure \(\mathsf{SpectrIn}\) (see Algorithm 2) for initialization. \(\mathsf{SpectrIn}\) is a spectral relaxation-based initialization technique. \(\mathsf{SpectrIn}\) computes the first \(d\) leading unit eigenvectors of the data matrix to form \(\bm{\Phi}\in\mathbb{R}^{nd\times d}\). We multiply \(\sqrt{n}\) to those eigenvectors to ensure that its norm matches that of \(\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}\). We also construct \(\bm{\Psi}\), which reverses the sign of the last column of \(\bm{\Phi}\) so that the determinants of \(\bm{\Phi}\) and \(\bm{\Psi}\) differ by a sign. Then, we compute the projection of \(\bm{\Phi}\) and \(\bm{\Psi}\) onto \(\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}\). The projection is computed in a block-wise manner, namely

\[\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}}_{i}=\mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{SO}(d)}(\bm{\Phi}_{i}),\quad 1 \leq i\leq n,\]

where \(\bm{\Phi}_{i},\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}}_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times d}\) are the \(i\)-th block of \(\bm{\Phi}\) and \(\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}}\), respectively.

The projection can be explicitly evaluated as

\[\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}}_{i}=\begin{cases}\bm{P}_{i}\bm{Q}_{i}^{\top},&\text{if } \det(\bm{\Phi}_{i})>0,\\ \widetilde{\bm{P}}_{i}\bm{Q}_{i}^{\top},&\text{otherwise},\end{cases}\quad 1\leq i\leq n.\]

Here, \(\bm{P}_{i},\bm{Q}_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times d}\) are the left and right singular vectors of \(\bm{\Phi}_{i}\) (with descending order of singular values), respectively, and \(\widehat{\bm{P}}_{i}\) is obtained by reversing the sign of the last column of \(\bm{P}_{i}\). The initial point \(\bm{X}^{0}\) is chosen as \(\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}}\) or \(\widetilde{\bm{\Psi}}\), depending on which is closer to \(\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}\).

Let us mention that the computation of \(\widetilde{\bm{\Psi}}\) and Steps 5 - 9 in \(\mathsf{SpectrIn}\) can practically improve the approximation error \(\mathrm{dist}(\bm{X}^{0},\bm{X}^{\star})\). We demonstrate such a phenomenon in Figure 1, in which "Naive \(\mathsf{SpectrIn}\)" refers to outputing \(\bm{X}^{0}=\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}}\) directly in Algorithm 2.

**Riemannian subgradient update.** ReSync then implements an iterative Riemannian subgradient procedure after obtaining the initial point \(\bm{X}^{0}\). The key is to compute the search direction (Riemannian subgradient) \(\widetilde{\nabla}_{\mathcal{R}}f(\bm{X}_{i}^{k})\) and the retraction \(\mathrm{Retr}_{\bm{X}_{i}^{k}}(\cdot)\) onto \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\) for \(1\leq i\leq n\). Towards providing concrete formulas for the Riemannian subgradient update, let us impose the Euclidean inner product \(\langle\bm{A},\bm{B}\rangle=\mathrm{trace}(\bm{A}^{\top}\bm{B})\) as the inherent Riemannian metric. Consequently, the tangent space to \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\) at \(\bm{R}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)\) is given by \(\mathrm{T}_{\bm{R}}:=\{\bm{R}\bm{S}:\bm{S}\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times d},\bm{S}+\bm {S}^{\top}=0\}\). The Riemannian subgradient \(\widetilde{\nabla}_{\mathcal{R}}f(\bm{X}_{i})\) can be computed as [40, Theorem 5.1]

\[\widetilde{\nabla}_{\mathcal{R}}f(\bm{X}_{i})=\mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{T}_{\bm{X} _{i}}}(\widetilde{\nabla}f(\bm{X}_{i})),\quad 1\leq i\leq n,\] (3)

where the projection can be computed as \(\mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{T}_{\bm{X}_{i}}}(\bm{B})=\bm{X}_{i}\big{(}\bm{X}_{i}^{ \top}\bm{B}-\bm{B}^{\top}\bm{X}_{i}\big{)}/2\) for any \(\bm{B}\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times d}\) and \(\widetilde{\nabla}f(\bm{X}_{i})\) is the Euclidean subgradient of \(f\) with respect to the \(i\)-th block variable \(\bm{X}_{i}\). Let us define \(f_{i,j}(\bm{X}):=\|\bm{X}_{i}\bm{X}_{j}^{\top}-\bm{Y}_{ij}\|_{F}\). The Euclidean subdifferential \(\partial f(\bm{X}_{i})\) with respect to the block variable \(\bm{X}_{i}\) is given by

