**Algorithm 2** SpectrIn: Spectral Initialization

Any element \(\widetilde{\nabla}f(\bm{X}_{i})\in\partial f(\bm{X}_{i})\) is called a Euclidean subgradient. In \(\mathsf{ReSync}\), one can choose an arbitrary subgradient \(\widetilde{\nabla}f(\bm{X}_{i})\in\partial f(\bm{X}_{i})\) at \(\bm{X}_{i}\).

Mimicking the gradient method to update along the search direction \(\widetilde{\nabla}_{\mathcal{R}}f(\bm{X}_{i})\) provides a point \(\bm{X}_{i}^{+}=\bm{X}_{i}-\mu\widetilde{\nabla}_{\mathcal{R}}f(\bm{X}_{i})\) on the tangent space \(\mathrm{T}_{\bm{X}_{i}}\) at \(\bm{X}_{i}\), which may violate the manifold constraint "\(\bm{X}_{i}^{+}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)\)". One common approach in Riemannian optimization is to employ a retraction operator to address the feasibility issue. For \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\), we can use a QR decomposition-based retraction and implement the Riemannian subgradient step as

\[\bm{X}_{i}^{+}=\mathrm{Retr}_{\bm{X}_{i}}\left(-\mu\widetilde{\nabla}_{ \mathcal{R}}f(\bm{X}_{i})\right)=\mathrm{Qr}\left(\bm{X}_{i}-\mu\widetilde{ \nabla}_{\mathcal{R}}f(\bm{X}_{i})\right),\quad 1\leq i\leq n.\] (4)

Here, \(\mathrm{Qr}(\bm{B})\) returns the Q-factor in the thin QR decomposition of \(\bm{B}\), while the diagonal entries of the R-factor are restricted to be positive [7].

Finally, setting \(\bm{X}_{i}=\bm{X}_{i}^{k}\), \(\bm{X}_{j}=\bm{X}_{j}^{k}\) for all \(j\) such that \((i,j)\in\mathcal{E}\), \(\mu=\mu_{k}\) in (3) and (4) yields a concrete implementation of Step 4 in \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) and leads to \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\ni\bm{X}_{i}^{k+1}=\bm{X}_{i}^{+}\) for \(1\leq i\leq n\). This completes the description of one full iteration of \(\mathsf{ReSync}\). Note that the per-iteration complexity of the Riemannian subgradient procedure is \(\mathcal{O}(n^{2}q)\), and Algorithm 2 has computational cost \(\mathcal{O}(n^{3})\).

### RCM Setup for Theoretical Analysis

We develop our theoretical analysis of \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) by adopting the random corruption model (\(\mathsf{RCM}\)). The \(\mathsf{RCM}\) was previously used in many works to analyze the performance of various synchronization algorithms; see, e.g., [39, 19, 23, 32]. Specifically, we can represent our measurement model (1) on a graph \(\mathcal{G}(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{E})\), where \(\mathcal{V}\) is a set of \(n\) nodes representing \(\{\bm{X}_{1}^{\star},\cdots,\bm{X}_{n}^{\star}\}\) and \(\mathcal{E}\) is a set of edgescontaining all the available measurements \(\{\bm{Y}_{i,j},(i,j)\in\mathcal{E}\}\). We assume that the graph \(\mathcal{G}\) follows the well-known Erdos-Renyi model \(\mathsf{G}(n,q)\), which implies that each edge \((i,j)\in\mathcal{E}\) is observed with probability \(q\), independently from every other edge. Each edge \((i,j)\in\mathcal{E}\) is a true observation (i.e., \((i,j)\in\mathcal{A}\)) with probability \(p\) and an outlier (i.e., \((i,j)\in\mathcal{A}^{\mathcal{E}}\)) with probability \(1-p\). Furthermore, the outliers \(\{\bm{O}_{i,j}\}_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{A}^{\mathcal{E}}}\) are assumed to be independently and uniformly distributed on \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\).

## 3 Main Results

In this section, we present our theoretical results for \(\mathsf{ReSync}\). Our main results are summarized in the following theorem, which states that our proposed algorithm can converge at a linear rate to the underlying rotations \(\bm{X}^{\star}\). Our standing assumption in this section is stated below.

All our theoretical results in this section are based on the RCM; see Section 2.2.

**Theorem 1** (overall).: _Suppose that the ratios \(p\) and \(q\) satisfy_

\[p^{7}q^{2}=\Omega\left(\frac{\log n}{n}\right).\]

_With probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n)\), \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) with \(\mu_{k}=\mu_{0}\gamma^{k}\), where \(\mu_{0}=\Theta(p^{2}/n)\) and \(\gamma=1-\frac{pq}{16}\), converges linearly to the ground-truth rotations \(\bm{X}^{\star}\) (up to a global rotation), i.e.,_

\[\mathrm{dist}\left(\bm{X}^{k},\bm{X}^{\star}\right)\leq\xi_{0} \gamma^{k},\quad\mathrm{dist}_{\infty}\left(\bm{X}^{k},\bm{X}^{\star}\right) \leq\delta_{0}\gamma^{k},\quad\forall k\geq 0.\]

_Here, \(\xi_{0}=\Theta(\sqrt{np^{5}q})\) and \(\delta_{0}=\Theta(p^{2})\)._

The basic idea of the proof is to establish the problem-intrinsic property of weak sharpness and then use it to derive a linear convergence result. However, the result only holds locally. Thus, we develop a procedure to initialize the algorithm in this local region and argue that \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) will not leave this region afterwards. In the remaining parts of this section, we implement the above ideas and highlight the challenges and approaches to overcoming them.

### Analysis of SpectrIn with Leave-One-Out Technique

**Theorem 2** (initialization).: _Let \(\bm{X}^{0}\) be generated by \(\mathsf{SpectrIn}\) (see Algorithm 2). Suppose that the ratios \(p\) and \(q\) satisfy_

\[p^{2}q=\Omega\left(\frac{\log n}{n}\right).\]

_Then, with probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n)\), we have_

\[\mathrm{dist}(\bm{X}^{0},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{ \sqrt{\log n}}{p\sqrt{q}}\right)\quad\text{and}\quad\mathrm{dist}_{\infty}( \bm{X}^{0},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\sqrt{\log n}}{p\sqrt{nq}} \right).\] (5)

The works [34] and [11] show that exact reconstruction of \(\bm{X}^{\star}\) is information-theoretically possible if the condition \(p^{2}q=\Omega\left(\log n/n\right)\) holds for the cases \(d=2\) and \(d=3\), respectively. Though Theorem 2 does not provide exact recovery, it achieves an optimal sample complexity for reconstructing an approximate solution in the infinity norm. Specifically, Theorem 2 shows that, as long as \(p^{2}q\geq C\log n/n\) for some constant \(C>0\) large enough, the \(\ell_{\infty}\)-distance \(\mathrm{dist}_{\infty}(\bm{X}^{0},\bm{X}^{\star})\) (i.e., \(\max_{1\leq i\leq n}\mathrm{dist}(\bm{X}_{i},\bm{X}_{i}^{\star})\)) can be made relatively small. However, the \(\ell_{2}\)-distance \(\mathrm{dist}(\bm{X}^{0},\bm{X}^{\star})\) is of the order \(\Omega(\sqrt{n})\) under such a sample complexity.

The work [26] considers orthogonal and permutation group synchronization and shows that spectral relaxation-based methods achieve near-optimal performance bounds. Our result differs from that of [26] in twofold: 1) Our approach follows the standard leave-one-out analysis based on the standard "\(\mathrm{Dist}\)" (up to \(\mathrm{O}(d)\) invariance) defined above Lemma 3 in the Appendix. Nonetheless, we have to transfer the results to "\(\mathrm{dist}\)" due to the structure of \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\) in Lemma 5, which is a nontrivial step due to the specific structure of \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\). 2) Our result can handle incomplete observations (i.e., \(q<1\)). In the case of incomplete observations, the construction in (17) in the Appendix becomes more intricate; it has the additional third column, rendering the analysis of our Lemma 2 more involved.

We prove Theorem 2 with some matrix concentration bounds and the leave-one-out technique. We provide the proof sketch below and refer to Appendix A for the full derivations.

**Proof outline of Theorem 2**. According to (1) and the fact \(\mathbb{E}(\bm{O}_{ij})=\bm{0}\) since outliers are assumed to be independently and uniformly distributed on \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\) in the RCM (see Appendix A), we know that \(\mathbb{E}(\bm{Y}_{ij})=pq\bm{X}_{i}^{\star}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star\top}\) for all \((i,j)\in[n]\times[n]\). This motivates us to introduce the noise matrix \(\bm{W}_{ij}=\bm{Y}_{ij}-pq\bm{X}_{i}^{\star}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star\top}\), i.e.,

\[\bm{Y}=pq\bm{X}^{\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top}+\bm{W}.\] (6)

The condition \(p^{2}q=\Omega(\log n/n)\) in Theorem 2 ensures that the expectation \(pq\bm{X}^{\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top}\) will dominate the noise matrix \(\bm{W}\) in the decomposition (6).

We first discuss how to bound \(\mathrm{dist}(\bm{X}^{0},\bm{X}^{\star})\). Notice that \(\bm{X}^{0}\) and \(\bm{X}^{\star}\) are the \(d\) leading eigenvectors of \(\bm{Y}\) (after projection onto \(\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}\)) and \(pq\bm{X}^{\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top}\), respectively. We can then use the matrix perturbation theory (see Lemma 3) to bound \(\mathrm{dist}(\bm{X}^{0},\bm{X}^{\star})\). Towards this end, we need to estimate the operator norm \(\|\bm{W}\|_{2}\), which could be done by applying the standard matrix Bernstein concentration inequality [38] since the blocks \(\{\bm{W}_{ij}\}\) are i.i.d. white noise with bounded operator norms and variances; see Lemma 2.

We next turn to bound the initialization error in the infinity norm, i.e., \(\mathrm{dist}_{\infty}(\bm{X}^{0},\bm{X}^{\star})\). Let us use \((\bm{W}\bm{X}^{0})_{m}\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times d}\) to denote the \(m\)-th block of \(\bm{W}\bm{X}^{0}\in\mathbb{R}^{nd\times d}\) for \(1\leq m\leq n\). The main technical challenge lies in deriving a sharp bound for the term \(\max_{1\leq m\leq n}\|(\bm{W}\bm{X}^{0})_{m}\|_{F}\), as it involves two _dependent_ random quantities, i.e., the noise matrix \(\bm{W}\) and the initial \(\bm{X}^{0}\) that is obtained by projecting the first \(d\) leading eigenvectors of \(\bm{Y}\) onto \(\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}\). To overcome such a statistical dependence, we utilize the leave-one-out technique. This technique was utilized in [42] to analyze the phase synchronization problem and was later applied to many other synchronization problems [1, 10, 15, 18, 26]. Let us define

\[\bm{Y}^{(m)}=pq\bm{X}^{\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top}+\bm{W}^{(m)}\quad\text{with} \quad\bm{W}_{kl}^{(m)}=\bm{W}_{kl}\cdot\bm{1}_{\{k\neq m\}}\cdot\bm{1}_{\{l\neq m \}}.\] (7)

That is, we construct \(\bm{W}^{(m)}\in\mathbb{R}^{nd\times nd}\) by setting the \(m\)-th block-wise row and column of \(\bm{W}\) to be \(\bm{0}\). Then, it is easy to see that \(\bm{Y}^{(m)}\) is statistically independent of \(\bm{W}_{m}^{\top}\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times nd}\), where the latter denotes the \(m\)-th block-wise row of \(\bm{W}\). Let \(\bm{X}^{(m)}\) be the \(d\) leading eigenvectors of \(\bm{Y}^{(m)}\). Consequently, \(\bm{X}^{(m)}\) is also independent of \(\bm{W}_{m}^{\top}\). Based on the above discussions, we can bound each \(\|(\bm{W}\bm{X}^{0})_{m}\|_{F}\) in the following way:

\[\|(\bm{W}\bm{X}^{0})_{m}\|_{F}=\|\bm{W}_{m}^{\top}\bm{X}^{0}\|_{F}\leq\|\bm{W} _{m}^{\top}\bm{X}^{(m)}\|_{F}+\|\bm{W}_{m}^{\top}(\bm{X}^{0}-\bm{X}^{(m)})\|_{ F}.\] (8)

The first term \(\|\bm{W}_{m}^{\top}\bm{X}^{(m)}\|_{F}\) can be bounded using an appropriate concentration inequality due to the statistical independence between \(\bm{W}_{m}^{\top}\) and \(\bm{X}^{(m)}\). The second term can be bounded as

\[\|\bm{W}_{m}^{\top}(\bm{X}^{0}-\bm{X}^{(m)})\|_{F}\leq\|\bm{W}_{m}\|_{2}\cdot \|\bm{X}^{0}-\bm{X}^{(m)}\|_{F},\]

in which \(\|\bm{W}_{m}\|_{2}\) can be further bounded by matrix concentration inequality (see Lemma 2) and \(\|\bm{X}^{0}-\bm{X}^{(m)}\|_{F}\) can be bounded using standard matrix perturbation theory (see Lemma 4).

### Weak Sharpness and Exact Recovery

We next present a property that is intrinsic to problem (2) in the following theorem.

**Theorem 3** (weak sharpness).: _Suppose that the ratios \(p\) and \(q\) satisfy_

\[p^{2}q^{2}=\Omega\left(\frac{\log n}{n}\right).\]

_Then, with probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n)\), for any \(\bm{X}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}\) satisfying \(\mathrm{dist}_{\infty}(\bm{X},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathcal{O}(p)\), we have_

\[f(\bm{X})-f(\bm{X}^{\star})\geq\frac{npq}{8}\,\mathrm{dist}_{1}(\bm{X},\bm{X}^{ \star}).\]

Some remarks on Theorem 3 are in order. This theorem shows that problem (2) possesses the _weak sharpness_ property [8], which is intrinsic to the problem and independent of the algorithm used to solve it. It is known that with this property, various subgradient-type methods can achieve linear convergence [14, 25]. We will establish a similar linear convergence result for \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) in the next subsection based on Theorem 3.

The weak sharpness property shown in Theorem 3 is of independent interest, as it could be helpful when analyzing other optimization algorithms (not just \(\mathsf{ReSync}\)) for solving problem (2). Currently,only a few applications are known to produce sharp optimization problems, such as robust low-rank matrix recovery [25], robust phase retrieval [16], and robust subspace recovery [24]. Furthermore, sharp instances of manifold optimization problems are especially scarce. Hence, Theorem 3 extends the list of optimization problems that possess the weak sharpness property and contributes to the growing literature on the geometry of structured nonsmooth nonconvex optimization problems.

It is worth noting that Theorem 3 also establishes the _exact recovery_ property of the formulation (2). Specifically, up to a global rotation, the ground-truth \(\bm{X}^{\star}\) is guaranteed to be the unique global minimizer of \(f\) over the region \(\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}\cap\{\bm{X}:\mathrm{dist}_{\infty}(\bm{X},\bm{X}^{\star})= \mathcal{O}(p)\}\). Consequently, recovering the underlying \(\bm{X}^{\star}\) reduces to finding the global minimizer of \(f\) over the aforementioned region. As we will show in the next subsection, ReSync will converge linearly to the global minimizer \(\bm{X}^{\star}\) when initialized in this region. However, the initialization requirement is subject to the stronger condition \(p^{4}q=\Omega\left(\log n/n\right)\) on the ratios \(p\) and \(q\), which is ensured by Theorem 2.

We list our main ideas for proving Theorem 3 below. The full proof can be found in Appendix B.

**Proof outline of Theorem 3**. Note that the objective function \(f\) can be decomposed into two parts:

\[f(\bm{X})=\overline{\sum_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{A}}\lVert\bm{X}_{i}^{\top}\bm{X}_{ j}-\bm{X}_{i}^{\star\top}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star}\rVert_{F}}+\overline{\sum_{(i,j)\in \mathcal{A}^{c}}\lVert\bm{X}_{i}^{\top}\bm{X}_{j}-\bm{O}_{ij}\rVert_{F}}\,.\] (9)

It is easy to see that \(g(\bm{X}^{\star})=0\) and \(g(\bm{X})\geq 0\). Based on the fact that the true observation is uniformly distributed in all the indices, we have \(\mathbb{E}\left(g(\bm{X})\right)=pq\sum_{1\leq i,j\leq n}\lVert\bm{X}_{i}^{ \top}\bm{X}_{j}-\bm{X}_{i}^{\star\top}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star}\rVert_{F}\geq\frac{ npq}{2}\operatorname{dist}_{1}(\bm{X},\bm{X}^{\star})\); see Appendix B.2 for the last inequality. A traditional way to lower bounding \(g(\bm{X})\) using \(\mathbb{E}(g(\bm{X}))\) for all \(\bm{X}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)\) is to apply concentration inequality and an epsilon-net covering argument. Unfortunately, the sample complexity condition \(p^{2}q^{2}=\Omega(\log n/n)\) does not lead to a high probability result in this way. Instead, our approach is to apply the concentration theory on the cardinalities of index sets rather than on \(\bm{X}\) directly; see the following lemma.

**Lemma 1** (concentration of cardinalities of index sets).: _Given any \(\epsilon=\Omega\left(\frac{\sqrt{\log n}}{\sqrt{np}q}\right)\), with probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n)\), we have_

\[(1-\epsilon)nq \leq\lvert\mathcal{E}_{i}\rvert\leq(1+\epsilon)nq, (1-\epsilon)npq\leq\lvert\mathcal{A}_{i}\rvert\leq(1+\epsilon)npq,\] \[(1-\epsilon)npq^{2} \leq\lvert\mathcal{E}_{i}\cap\mathcal{A}_{j}\rvert\leq(1+\epsilon )npq^{2}, (1-\epsilon)np^{2}q^{2}\leq\lvert\mathcal{A}_{ij}\rvert\leq(1+\epsilon)np^{2 }q^{2}\]

_for any \(1\leq i,j\leq n\). See Section 1 for the notation._

We then provide a sharp lower bound on \(g(\bm{X})\) based on Lemma 1.

**Proposition 1**.: _Under the conditions of Theorem 3, with probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n)\), we have_

\[g(\bm{X})\geq\frac{3npq}{16}\operatorname{dist}_{1}\left(\bm{X},\bm{X}^{\star }\right),\quad\forall\bm{X}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}.\] (10)

Next, to lower bound \(h(\bm{X})-h(\bm{X}^{\star})=\sum_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{A}^{c}}\left(\lVert\bm{X}_ {i}^{\top}\bm{X}_{j}-\bm{O}_{ij}\rVert_{F}-\lVert\bm{X}_{i}^{\star\top}\bm{X}_ {j}^{\star}-\bm{O}_{ij}\rVert_{F}\right)\) we first bound

\[h(\bm{X})-h(\bm{X}^{\star})\geq\sum_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{A}^{c}}\left\langle\frac {\bm{X}_{i}^{\top}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star}-\bm{O}_{ij}}{\lVert\bm{X}_{i}^{\star\top} \bm{X}_{j}^{\star}-\bm{O}_{ij}\rVert_{F}},\bm{X}_{i}^{\top}\bm{X}_{j}-\bm{X}_ {i}^{\star\top}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star}\right\rangle,\]

where the inequality comes from the convexity of the norm function \(\bm{U}\mapsto\lVert\bm{U}\rVert_{F}\) whenever \(\bm{X}_{i}^{\star\top}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star}-\bm{O}_{ij}\neq\bm{0}\). Then, using the orthogonality of each block of \(\bm{X}^{\star}\), we further have

\[h(\bm{X})-h(\bm{X}^{\star})\geq\sum_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{A}^{c}}\left\langle\frac {\bm{I}-\bm{X}_{i}^{\star}\bm{O}_{ij}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star\top}}{\lVert\bm{I}- \bm{X}_{i}^{\star}\bm{O}_{ij}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star\top}\rVert_{F}},\bm{X}_{i}^{ \star}\bm{X}_{i}^{\top}\bm{X}_{j}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star\top}-\bm{I}\right\rangle.\] (11)

Recall that since the outliers \(\{\bm{O}_{i,j}\}_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{A}^{c}}\) are independently and uniformly distributed on \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\), so are \(\{\bm{X}_{i}^{\star}\bm{O}_{ij}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star\top}\}_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{A}^{c}}\). This observation indicates that \(\left\{\bm{I}-\bm{X}_{i}^{\star}\bm{O}_{ij}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star\top}/\lVert\bm{I} -\bm{X}_{i}^{\star}\bm{O}_{ij}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star\top}\rVert_{F}\right\}_{(i,j) \in\mathcal{A}^{c}}\) are i.i.d. random matrices. Hence, by invoking concentration results that utilize the randomness of the outliers \(\{\bm{O}_{i,j}\}_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{A}^{c}}\) and the cardinalities \((i,j)\in\mathcal{A}^{c}\), we obtain the following result.

**Proposition 2**.: _Under the conditions of Theorem 3, with probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n)\), we have_

\[h(\bm{X})-h(\bm{X}^{\star})\geq-\frac{npq}{16}\operatorname{dist}_{1}\left(\bm{X },\bm{X}^{\star}\right)\] (12)

_for all \(\bm{X}\in\operatorname{SO}(d)^{n}\) satisfying \(\operatorname{dist}_{\infty}(\bm{X},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathcal{O}(p)\)._

Combining Proposition 1 and Proposition 2 gives Theorem 3.

### Convergence Analysis and Proof of Theorem 1

Let us now turn to utilize the weak sharpness property shown in Theorem 3 to establish the local linear convergence of \(\mathsf{ReSync}\). As a quick corollary of Theorem 3, we have the following result.

**Corollary 1**.: _Under the conditions of Theorem 3, with probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n)\), for any \(\bm{X}\in\operatorname{SO}(d)^{n}\) satisfying \(\operatorname{dist}_{\infty}(\bm{X},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathcal{O}(p)\), we have_

\[\left\langle\widetilde{\nabla}_{\mathcal{R}}f(\bm{X}),\bm{X}^{\star}-\bm{X} \right\rangle\leq-\frac{npq}{16}\operatorname{dist}_{1}(\bm{X},\bm{X}^{\star }),\quad\forall\ \widetilde{\nabla}_{\mathcal{R}}f(\bm{X})\in\partial_{\mathcal{R}}f(\bm{X}).\] (13)

This condition indicates that any Riemannian subgradient \(\widetilde{\nabla}_{\mathcal{R}}f(\bm{X})\) provides a descent direction pointing towards \(\bm{X}^{\star}\). However, it only holds for \(\bm{X}\in\operatorname{SO}(d)^{n}\) satisfying \(\operatorname{dist}_{\infty}(\bm{X},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathcal{O}(p)\). Our key idea for establishing local convergence is to show that the Riemannian subgradient update in \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) is a contraction operator _in both the Euclidean and infinity norm-induced distances_ using Corollary 1, i.e., if \(\bm{X}^{k}\) lies in the local region, then \(\bm{X}^{k+1}\) also lies in the region. This idea motivates us to define two sequences of neighborhoods as follows:

\[\mathcal{N}_{F}^{k}=\{\bm{X}\mid\operatorname{dist}(\bm{X},\bm{X}^{\star}) \leq\xi_{k}\}\quad\text{ and }\quad\mathcal{N}_{\infty}^{k}=\{\bm{X}\mid \operatorname{dist}_{\infty}(\bm{X},\bm{X}^{\star})\leq\delta_{k}\}\,.\] (14)

Here, \(\xi_{k}=\xi_{0}\gamma^{k},\delta_{k}=\delta_{0}\gamma^{k}\), where \(\xi_{0}\), \(\delta_{0}\), and \(\gamma\in(0,1)\) will be specified later. Thus, these two sequences of sets \(\{\mathcal{N}_{F}^{k}\}\) and \(\{\mathcal{N}_{\infty}^{k}\}\) will linearly shrink to the ground-truth. It remains to show that if \(\bm{X}^{k}\in\mathcal{N}_{F}^{k}\cap\mathcal{N}_{\infty}^{k}\), then \(\bm{X}^{k+1}\in\mathcal{N}_{F}^{k+1}\cap\mathcal{N}_{\infty}^{k+1}\), which is summarized in the following theorem.

**Theorem 4** (convergence analysis).: _Suppose that \(\delta_{0}=\mathcal{O}(p^{2})\) and \(\xi_{0}=\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{npq}\delta_{0})\). Set \(\gamma=1-\frac{pq}{16}\) and \(\mu_{k}=\delta_{k}/n\) in \(\mathsf{ReSync}\). If \(\bm{X}^{k}\in\mathcal{N}_{F}^{k}\cap\mathcal{N}_{\infty}^{k}\) for any \(k\geq 0\), then with probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n)\), we have_

\[\bm{X}^{k+1}\in\mathcal{N}_{F}^{k+1}\cap\mathcal{N}_{\infty}^{k+1}.\]

**Proof outline of Theorem 4.** The proof consisted of two parts. On the one hand, we need to show that \(\bm{X}^{k+1}\in\mathcal{N}_{F}^{k+1}\), which can be achieved by applying Corollary 1. On the other hand, in order to show that \(\bm{X}^{k+1}\in\mathcal{N}_{\infty}^{k+1}\), we need a good estimate of each block of \(\widetilde{\nabla}_{\mathcal{R}}f(\bm{X})\). See Appendix C.

Having developed the necessary tools, we are now ready to prove Theorem 1.

**Proof of Theorem 1.** Based on Theorem 2, we know that \(\bm{X}^{0}\in\mathcal{N}_{F}^{0}\bigcap\mathcal{N}_{\infty}^{0}\) if \(\xi_{0}\) and \(\delta_{0}\) satisfy

\[\xi_{0}=\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\sqrt{\log n}}{p\sqrt{q}}\right)\quad\text{ and}\quad\delta_{0}=\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\sqrt{\log n}}{p\sqrt{nq}}\right).\] (15)

According to Theorem 4, by choosing \(\delta_{0}=\Theta(p^{2})\) and \(\xi_{0}=\Theta(\sqrt{np^{5}q})\), condition (15) holds when \(p^{7}q^{2}=\Omega\left(\log n/n\right)\). This completes the proof of Theorem 1.

## 4 Experiments

In this section, we conduct experiments on \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) for solving the \(\mathsf{RRS}\) problem on both synthetic and real data, providing empirical support for our theoretical findings. Our experiments are conducted on a personal computer with a 2.90GHz 8-core CPU and 32GB memory. All our experiment results are averaged over 20 independent trials. Our code is available at https://github.com/Huikang2019/\(\mathsf{ReSync}\).

### Synthetic Data

We consider the rotation group \(\operatorname{SO}(3)\) in all our experiments. We generate \(\bm{X}_{1}^{\star},\ldots,\bm{X}_{n}^{\star}\) by first generating matrices of the same dimension with i.i.d. standard Gaussian entries and then projectingeach of them onto \(\mathrm{SO}(3)\). The underlying graph, outliers, and relative rotations in the measurement model (1) are generated according to the \(\mathsf{RCM}\) as described in Section 2.2. In our experiments, we also consider the case where the true observations are contaminated by additive noise, namely, \(\{\bm{Y}_{i,j}\}_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{A}}\) in (1) is generated using the formula

\[\bm{Y}_{i,j}=\mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{SO}(3)}\left(\bm{X}_{i}^{\ast\top}\bm{X}_{j}^ {\ast}+\sigma\bm{G}_{i,j}\right)\quad\text{for}\quad(i,j)\in\mathcal{A},\] (16)

where \(\bm{G}_{i,j}\) consists of i.i.d. entries following the standard Gaussian distribution and \(\sigma\geq 0\) controls the variance level of the noise.

**Convergence verification of ReSync.** We evaluate the convergence performance of \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) with the noise level \(\sigma=0\) in (16). We set \(p=q=(\log n/n)^{1/3}\) in the measurement model (1), which satisfies \(p^{2}q=\log n/n\). We use the initial step size \(\mu_{0}=1/npq\) and the decaying factor \(\gamma\in\{0.7,0.8,0.85,0.90,0.95,0.98\}\) in \(\mathsf{ReSync}\). We test the performance for various \(n\) selected from \(\{400,600,800,1000\}\). Figure 2 displays the experiment results. It can be observed that (i) \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) converges linearly to ground-truth rotations for a wide range of \(\gamma\) and (ii) a smaller \(\gamma\) often leads to faster convergence speed. These corroborate our theoretical findings. However, it is worth noting that excessively small \(\gamma\) values may result in an early stopping phenomenon (e.g., \(\gamma\leq 0.8\) when \(n=400\)). In addition, \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) performs better with a larger \(n\), as it allows for a smaller \(\gamma\) (e.g., \(\gamma=0.7\) when \(n=1000\)) and hence converges to the ground-truth rotations faster.

**Comparison with the state-of-the-arts.** We next compare \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) with state-of-the-art synchronization algorithms, including IRLS_L12 [9], MPLS [31], CEMP_GCW [23, 32], DESC [32], and LUD [39]. We obtain the implementation of the first four algorithms from https://github.com/ColeWyeth/DESC, while LUD's implementation is obtained through private communication with its authors. In our comparisons, we use their default parameter settings. For \(\mathsf{ReSync}\), we set the initial step size to \(\mu_{0}=1/npq\) and the decaying factor to \(\gamma=0.95\), as suggested by the previous experiment. We fix \(n=200\) and vary the true observation ratio \(p\) (or the observation ratio \(q\)) while keeping \(q=0.2\) (or \(p=0.2\)) fixed. We display the experiment results for \(\sigma=0\) and \(\sigma=1\) in Figures 2(a) and 2(b), respectively, where \(p\) is selected from \(\{0.2,0.3,0.4,\dots,1\}\). When \(\sigma=0\), \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) achieves competitive performance compared to other robust synchronization algorithms. When the additive noise level is \(\sigma=1\), \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) outperforms other algorithms. In Figures 2(c) and 2(d), we present the results with varying \(q\) chosen from \(\{0.2,0.3,0.4,\dots,1\}\) for noise-free (\(\sigma=0\)) and noisy (\(\sigma=1\)) cases, respectively. In the noise-free case, DESC performs best when \(q<0.5\), while \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) slightly outperforms others when \(q\geq 0.5\). In the noisy case, it is clear that \(\mathsf{ReSync}\) achieves the best performance for a large range of \(q\).

