Full Proof of Theorem 2

In this section, we present the full proof of Theorem 2. We will use the notation defined in the proof outline of Theorem 2 in Section 3.1.

Firstly, we know that

\[\bm{W}_{ij}=\begin{cases}(1-pq)\bm{X}_{i}^{\star}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star\top},&\text{ with probablity }pq,\\ \bm{O}_{ij}-pq\bm{X}_{i}^{\star}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star\top},&\text{with probablity }(1-p)q,\\ -pq\bm{X}_{i}^{\star}\bm{X}_{j}^{\star\top},&\text{otherwise}.\end{cases}\] (17)

Since \(\bm{O}_{ij}\) is assumed to be uniformly distributed on \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\) in the RCM, given any matrix \(\bm{Q}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)\), it is easy to see that \(\bm{O}_{ij}\bm{Q}\) is also uniformly distributed on \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\), so we have

\[\mathbb{E}(\bm{O}_{ij})=\mathbb{E}(\bm{O}_{ij}\bm{Q})=\mathbb{E}(\bm{O}_{ij}) \cdot\bm{Q},\quad\forall\bm{Q}\in\mathrm{SO}(d).\]

Let \(\bm{E}_{kl}\in\mathrm{SO}(d),k\neq l\) denote the diagonal matrix whose \(k\)-th and \(l\)-th diagonal entries are \(-1\) and others are \(1\), then we have \(\mathbb{E}(\bm{O}_{ij})=\mathbb{E}(\bm{O}_{ij})\cdot\bm{E}_{kl}\), which implies

\[d\mathbb{E}(\bm{O}_{ij})=\mathbb{E}(\bm{O}_{ij})\cdot(\bm{E}_{12}+\bm{E}_{23 }+\cdots+\bm{E}_{d1})=(d-4)\mathbb{E}(\bm{O}_{ij}).\]

Thus, we have \(\mathbb{E}(\bm{O}_{ij})=\bm{0}\). Then, it is easy to see that \(\mathbb{E}(\bm{W}_{ij})=0\) and

\[\mathrm{Var}(\bm{W}_{ij})=(1-pq)^{2}\bm{I}+(1-q)p^{2}q^{2}\bm{I}+(1-p)q(1+p^{ 2}q^{2})\bm{I}=q(1-p^{2}q)\bm{I}.\] (18)

Based on the above calculations, we can derive the following Lemma, which is a direct result of the matrix Bernstein inequality [38]. Similar results can also be found in [42, Lemma 9], [27, Proposition 3], and [26, Eq. (5.12)].

**Lemma 2**.: _With probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n)\), the following holds for any \(m\in[n]\):_

\[\|\bm{W}\|_{2}=\mathcal{O}\left(\sqrt{nq\log n}\right),\quad\|\bm{W}^{(m)}\|_ {2}=\mathcal{O}\left(\sqrt{nq\log n}\right),\quad\|\bm{W}_{m}\|_{2}=\mathcal{ O}\left(\sqrt{nq\log n}\right).\]

Proof.: Note that \(\bm{W}=\sum_{i<j}\bm{W}^{(ij)},\) where \(\bm{W}^{(ij)}\in\mathbb{R}^{nd\times nd}\) denotes the matrix with the \((i,j)\) and \((j,i)\)-th block equal to \(\bm{W}_{ij}\) and \(\bm{W}_{ji}\) and others equal to 0. So \(\{\bm{W}^{(ij)}\}\) are i.i.d. centered and bounded random matrices. Besides, we have

\[\left\|\mathbb{E}(\bm{W}\bm{W}^{\top})\right\|_{2}=\left\|\sum_{i<j}\mathbb{E }(\bm{W}^{(ij)}(\bm{W}^{(ij)})^{\top})\right\|_{2}=2(n-1)\|\mathrm{Var}(\bm{W} _{ij})\|_{2}=\mathcal{O}(nq).\]

According to the matrix Bernstein inequality [38], we have that \(\|\bm{W}\|_{2}=\mathcal{O}\left(\sqrt{nq\log n}\right)\) holds with probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n^{2})\). The above argument also holds for each \(\bm{W}^{(m)}\), then taking a union bound over the choice of \(m\in[n]\) yields the second result. For \(\bm{W}_{m}\), we have

\[\|\bm{W}\|_{2}=\max_{\|\bm{u}\|_{2}=1}\|\bm{W}\bm{u}\|_{2}\geq\max_{\|\bm{u}\| _{2}=1}\|\bm{W}_{m}\bm{u}\|_{2}=\|\bm{W}_{m}\|_{2},\]

which gives the last result. 

The following lemma follows from [13]; see also [26, Theorem A.2]. [42, Lemma 11] is a special case where \(d=1\). Before that, we need to introduce the distance up to a global orthogonal matrix:

\[\mathrm{Dist}\left(\bm{X},\bm{Y}\right)=\|\bm{X}-\bm{Y}\bm{R}^{\star}\|_{F}, \text{ where }\bm{R}^{\star}=\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{\bm{R}\in O(d)}\|\bm{X}\bm{R}-\bm{Y} \|_{F}^{2}=\mathcal{P}_{O(d)}(\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{Y}).\]

**Lemma 3** (Davis-Kahan \(\sin\Theta\) Theorem).: _Suppose that \(\bm{A},\bm{E}\in\mathcal{C}^{n\times n}\) are Hermitian matrices and \(\tilde{\bm{A}}=\bm{A}+\bm{E}\). Let \(\delta=\lambda_{d}(\bm{A})-\lambda_{d+1}(\bm{A})>0\) be the gap between the \(d\)-th eigenvalue and \(d+1\)-th eigenvalue of \(\bm{A}\) for some \(1\leq d\leq n-1\). Furthermore, let \(\bm{U},\tilde{\bm{U}}\) be the \(d\)-leading eigenvectors of \(\bm{A}\) and \(\tilde{\bm{A}}\), respectively, which are normalized such that \(\|\bm{U}\|_{F}=\|\tilde{\bm{U}}\|_{F}=\sqrt{nd}\). Then, we have_

\[\mathrm{Dist}(\bm{U},\tilde{\bm{U}})\leq\frac{\sqrt{2}\|\bm{E}\bm{U}\|_{F}}{ \delta-\|\bm{E}\|_{2}}.\] (19)

### Initialization Error in Euclidean Norm

Based on Lemma 2 and Lemma 3, we have the following bound on \(\mathrm{Dist}\). Note that the notations \(\bm{\Phi},\bm{\Psi},\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}},\widetilde{\bm{\Psi}}\) used in the following analysis are defined in \(\mathsf{SpectrIn}\) (i.e., Algorithm 2).

**Lemma 4**.: _Let \(\bm{\Phi}\) and \(\bm{\Phi}^{(m)}\) be the \(d\)-leading eigenvectors of \(\bm{Y}\) and \(\bm{Y}^{(m)}\), respectively, which are normalized such that \(\|\bm{\Phi}\|_{F}=\|\bm{\Phi}^{(m)}\|_{F}=\sqrt{nd}\). Then, we have_

\[\mathrm{Dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\sqrt{\log n}}{p \sqrt{q}}\right)\quad\text{and}\quad\mathrm{Dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{\Phi}^{(m)})= \mathcal{O}(1)\] (20)

_hold with probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n)\)._

Proof.: Let us Choose \(\bm{A}=\bm{Y}^{(m)}\) and \(\bm{E}=\Delta\bm{W}^{(m)}=\bm{W}-\bm{W}^{(m)}\) in Lemma 3, then \(\tilde{\bm{A}}=\bm{Y}\), \(\bm{U}=\bm{\Phi}^{(m)}\) and \(\tilde{\bm{U}}=\bm{\Phi}\). Since \(\bm{\Phi}^{(m)}\) is independent of \(\Delta\bm{W}^{(m)}\), similar to Lemma 2, we apply the matrix Bernstein inequality [38] to obtain, with probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n^{2})\), that

\[\|\bm{E}\bm{U}\|_{F}=\|\Delta\bm{W}^{(m)}\bm{\Phi}^{(m)}\|_{F}=\mathcal{O}( \sqrt{nq\log n}).\]

In addition, \(\bm{Y}^{(m)}=pq\bm{X}^{\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top}+\bm{W}^{(m)}\) implies that

\[\delta=\lambda_{d}(\bm{Y}^{(m)})-\lambda_{d+1}(\bm{Y}^{(m)})\geq\lambda_{d}( pq\bm{X}^{\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top})-\|\bm{W}^{(m)}\|_{2}\geq npq-\mathcal{O}( \sqrt{nq\log n}).\]

where the second inequality holds due to \(\lambda_{d}(\bm{X}^{\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top})=n\) and the last inequality is from \(\lambda_{d}(\bm{X}^{\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top})=n\) and Lemma 2. Based on the condition that \(p^{2}q=\Omega\left(\frac{\log n}{n}\right)\), as long as \(p^{2}q\geq\frac{C\log n}{n}\) for some large enough constant \(C\), we have

\[\delta-\|\bm{E}\|_{2}\geq npq-\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{nq\log n})-\|\bm{E}\|_{2}\geq npq -\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{nq\log n})\geq\frac{1}{2}npq,\]

where the second inequality holds because of \(\|\bm{E}\|_{2}\leq\|\bm{W}\|_{2}+\|\bm{W}^{(m)}\|_{2}=\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{nq \log n})\). Hence, by applying Lemma 3, we get

\[\mathrm{Dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{\Phi}^{(m)})\leq\frac{\sqrt{2}\|\bm{E}\bm{U}\|_{F} }{\delta-\|\bm{E}\|_{2}}\leq\frac{\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{nq\log n})}{npq}=\mathcal{ O}(1)\] (21)

where the last inequality is because of \(p\sqrt{q}=\Omega(\sqrt{\log n/n})\). Similarly, by choosing \(\bm{A}=pq\bm{X}^{\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top}\) and \(\bm{E}=\bm{W}\), we can show that

\[\mathrm{Dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{\star})\leq\frac{\sqrt{2}\|\bm{W}\bm{X}^{ \star}\|_{F}}{npq-\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{nq\log n})}\leq\frac{\sqrt{2}\|\bm{W}\|_{2} \|\bm{X}^{\star}\|_{F}}{\frac{1}{2}npq}=\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\sqrt{\log n} }{p\sqrt{q}}\right).\]

Here, the last inequality holds because \(\|\bm{W}\|_{2}=\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{nq\log n})\) (see Lemma 2) and the fact that \(\|\bm{X}^{\star}\|_{F}=\sqrt{nd}\). 

Following the same analysis as in Lemma 4, we are also able to show that \(\mathrm{Dist}(\bm{\Psi},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\sqrt{\log n}}{ p\sqrt{q}}\right)\), where \(\bm{\Psi}\) reverses the sign of the last column of \(\bm{\Phi}\) so that the determinants of \(\bm{\Phi}\) and \(\bm{\Psi}\) differ by a sign. However, Lemma 4 only provides the upper bound on "\(\mathrm{Dist}\)", i.e., the distance up to an orthogonal matrix. The following lemma translates the result to that on "\(\mathrm{dist}\)".

**Lemma 5**.: _Suppose that \(\|\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}}-\bm{\Phi}\|_{F}\leq\|\widetilde{\bm{\Psi}}-\bm{\Psi}\|_ {F}\), where \(\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}}=\mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}}(\bm{\Phi})\) and \(\widetilde{\bm{\Psi}}=\mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}}(\bm{\Psi})\), then we have_

\[\mathrm{dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathrm{Dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{\star})= \mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\sqrt{\log n}}{p\sqrt{q}}\right).\]

Proof.: Based on the structure of \(O(d)\) and \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\), it is easy to see that

\[\mathrm{Dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{\star})=\min\left\{\mathrm{dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{ X}^{\star}),\mathrm{dist}(\bm{\Psi},\bm{X}^{\star})\right\}.\]

Our remaining task is to prove \(\mathrm{Dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathrm{dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{\star})\) based on the condition that \(\|\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}}-\bm{\Phi}\|_{F}\leq\|\widetilde{\bm{\Psi}}-\bm{\Psi}\|_ {F}\). If \(\mathrm{Dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathrm{dist}(\bm{\Psi},\bm{X}^{\star})\), then we have

\[\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\sqrt{\log n}}{p\sqrt{q}}\right)=\mathrm{Dist}(\bm{ \Phi},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathrm{dist}(\bm{\Psi},\bm{X}^{\star})\geq\|\widetilde{ \bm{\Psi}}-\bm{\Psi}\|_{F}\geq\|\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}}-\bm{\Phi}\|_{F}\]where the first inequality holds because \(\widetilde{\bm{\Psi}}\) is the projection of \(\bm{\Psi}\) on \(\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}\). It is easy to see that

\[\|\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}}-\bm{\Phi}\|_{F}+\|\widetilde{\bm{\Psi}}-\bm{\Psi}\|_{F}= \|\bm{\Phi}-\mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}}(\bm{\Phi})\|_{F}+\|\bm{\Phi}- \mathcal{P}_{(O(d)\setminus\mathrm{SO}(d))^{n}}(\bm{\Phi})\|_{F}\geq 2\sqrt{n}.\]

The equality holds because the mapping that reverses the sign of the last column of a matrix is a bijection between \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\) and \(O(d)\setminus\mathrm{SO}(d)\), and the inequality holds since the minimum distance between \(\mathrm{SO}(d)\) and \(O(d)\setminus\mathrm{SO}(d)\) is \(2\). Under the condition that \(p^{2}q=\Omega\left(\frac{\log n}{n}\right)\), as long as \(p^{2}q\geq\frac{C\log n}{n}\) for some large enough constant \(C\), we could have \(\|\widetilde{\bm{\Phi}}-\bm{\Phi}\|_{F}+\|\widetilde{\bm{\Psi}}-\bm{\Psi}\|_{ F}=\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\sqrt{\log n}}{p\sqrt{q}}\right)<2\sqrt{n}\), which contradict to the above inequality. Thus, we have

\[\mathrm{dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathrm{Dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{\star} )=\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\sqrt{\log n}}{p\sqrt{q}}\right).\]

### Initialization Error in Infinity Norm

Next, based on the Davis-Kahan theorem, we can bound the distance between \(\widetilde{\bm{X}}^{0}\) and \(\bm{X}^{\star}\) in the infinity norm, which is stated in the following result.

**Lemma 6**.: _Let \(\bm{\Phi}\) be the \(d\)-leading eigenvectors of \(\bm{Y}\). Then, we have_

\[\mathrm{dist}_{\infty}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{\star})=\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\sqrt{ \log n}}{p\sqrt{nq}}\right)\] (22)

_holds with probability at least \(1-\mathcal{O}(1/n)\)._

Proof.: Let \(\bm{\Pi}^{m}=\text{argmin}_{\bm{\Pi}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)}\|\bm{\Phi}-\bm{\Phi}^{( m)}\bm{\Pi}\|_{F}\). We can compute

\[\|(\bm{W}\bm{\Phi})_{m}\|_{F}=\|\bm{W}_{m}^{\top}\bm{\Phi}\|_{F} \leq\|\bm{W}_{m}^{\top}\bm{\Phi}^{(m)}\bm{\Pi}^{m}\|_{F}+\|\bm{W}_ {m}^{\top}(\bm{\Phi}-\bm{\Phi}^{(m)}\bm{\Pi}^{m})\|_{F}\] (23) \[\leq\|\bm{W}_{m}^{\top}\bm{\Phi}^{(m)}\|_{F}+\|\bm{W}_{m}\|_{2}\| \bm{\Phi}-\bm{\Phi}^{(m)}\bm{\Pi}^{m}\|_{F}.\]

The fact that \(\bm{\Phi}^{(m)}\) is independent from \(\bm{W}_{m}\) implies \(\|\bm{W}_{m}^{\top}\bm{\Phi}^{(m)}\|_{F}=\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{nq\log n})\), so we have

\[\|(\bm{W}\bm{\Phi})_{m}\|_{F}=\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{nq\log n})\left(1+\mathcal{O} (1)\right)=\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{nq\log n}).\] (24)

Next, let \(\bm{\Pi}^{\star}=\text{argmin}_{\bm{\Pi}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)}\|\bm{\Phi}-\bm{X}^ {\star}\bm{\Pi}\|_{F}\), then we have

\[(\bm{Y}\bm{\Phi})_{m}=pq\bm{X}_{m}^{\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top}\bm{\Phi}+(\bm{W} \bm{\Phi})_{m}=npq\bm{X}_{m}^{\star}\bm{\Pi}^{\star}+pq\bm{X}_{m}^{\star}\bm{ X}^{\star\top}(\bm{\Phi}-\bm{X}^{\star}\bm{\Pi}^{\star})+(\bm{W}\bm{\Phi})_{m}.\]

Since \(\bm{\Phi}\) is the \(d\)-leading eigenvector of \(\bm{Y}\), we have \(\bm{Y}\bm{\Phi}=\bm{\Phi}\bm{\Sigma}\) with \(\bm{\Sigma}\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times d}\) consisting of the \(d\)-leading eigenvalues of \(\bm{Y}\). Applying the standard eigenvalue perturbation theory, e.g., [37, Theorem 4.11], we have

\[\|\bm{\Sigma}-npq\bm{I}\|_{2}=\mathcal{O}(\|\bm{W}\|_{2})=\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{nq \log n}).\]

Based on the assumption that \(p^{2}q=\Omega\left(\frac{\log n}{n}\right)\), we can show that \(\bm{\Sigma}\geq\frac{3}{4}npq\bm{I}\). Note that \(\bm{Y}\bm{\Phi}=\bm{\Phi}\bm{\Sigma}\) implies \(\bm{\Phi}_{m}=(\bm{Y}\bm{\Phi})_{m}\bm{\Sigma}^{-1}\) for each \(m\in[n]\), then we have

\[\|\bm{\Phi}_{m}\|_{F}\leq\frac{4}{3npq}\|(\bm{Y}\bm{\Phi})_{m}\|_{F}\leq\frac{ 4}{3npq}\|pq\bm{X}_{m}^{\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top}\bm{\Phi}_{m}\|_{F}+\frac{4}{3 npq}\|(\bm{W}\bm{\Phi})_{m}\|_{F}\leq 2\sqrt{d},\]

where the last inequality holds because \(\frac{4}{3npq}\|pq\bm{X}_{m}^{\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top}\bm{\Phi}_{m}\|_{F}=\frac{ 4}{3n}\|\bm{X}^{\star\top}\bm{\Phi}_{m}\|_{F}\leq\frac{4\sqrt{d}}{3}\) and (24). Therefore, for each \(m\in[n]\),

\[npq(\bm{\Phi}_{m}-\bm{X}_{m}^{\star}\bm{\Pi}^{\star}) =\bm{\Phi}_{m}(npq\bm{I}-\bm{\Sigma})+\bm{\Phi}_{m}\bm{\Sigma}-npq \bm{X}_{m}^{\star}\bm{\Pi}^{\star}\] \[=\bm{\Phi}_{m}(npq\bm{I}-\bm{\Sigma})+(\bm{Y}\bm{\Phi})_{m}-npq \bm{X}_{m}^{\star}\bm{\Pi}^{\star}.\]

This further implies

\[npq\|\bm{\Phi}_{m}-\bm{X}_{m}^{\star}\bm{\Pi}^{\star}\|_{F}\leq \|\bm{\Sigma}-npq\bm{I}\|_{2}\|\bm{\Phi}_{m}\|_{F}+pq\|\bm{X}_{m}^ {\star}\bm{X}^{\star\top}(\bm{\Phi}-\bm{X}^{\star}\bm{\Pi}^{\star})\|_{F}+\|( \bm{W}\bm{\Phi})_{m}\|_{F}\] \[\leq 2\sqrt{d}\|\bm{W}\|_{2}+\sqrt{n}pq\|\bm{\Phi}-\bm{X}^{\star}\bm{ \Pi}^{\star}\|_{F}+\mathcal{O}\sqrt{nq(\log n)}\] \[= \mathcal{O}(\sqrt{nq\log n}),\]

where the last inequality holds because of Lemma 2 and Lemma 4. This completes the proof.

Finally, since \(\bm{X}^{0}=\mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}}(\bm{\Phi})\), according to Lemma 2 in [27], we have

\[\mathrm{dist}(\bm{X}^{0},\bm{X}^{\star})\leq 2\,\mathrm{dist}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{ \star})\quad\text{and}\quad\mathrm{dist}_{\infty}(\bm{X}^{0},\bm{X}^{\star}) \leq 2\,\mathrm{dist}_{\infty}(\bm{\Phi},\bm{X}^{\star}),\]

which complete the proof of Theorem 2.

## Appendix B Full Proof of Theorem 3

In this section, we provide the full proof of Lemma 1, Proposition 1, and Proposition 2, which finishes the proof of Theorem 3. To simplify the notation and the theoretical derivations, we assume without loss of generality that \(\bm{X}^{\star}_{i}=\bm{I}\) for all \(1\leq i\leq n\) as one can separately rotate the space that each variable \(\bm{X}_{i}\) lies in such that the corresponding ground-truth \(\bm{X}^{\star}_{i}\) is rotated to identity [39, Lemma 4.1]. Consequently, we have \(\bm{Y}_{ij}=\bm{I}\) for \((i,j)\in\mathcal{A}\).

### Proof of Lemma 1

For each \(1\leq i\leq n\), \(|\mathcal{E}_{i}|=\sum_{1\leq j\leq n}\bm{1}_{\mathcal{E}_{i}}(j)\), where \(\bm{1}_{\mathcal{E}_{i}}(\cdot)\) denotes the indicator function w.r.t \(\mathcal{E}_{i}\). Based on our model, \(\sum_{1\leq j\leq n}\bm{1}_{\mathcal{E}_{i}}(j)\) follows the binomial distribution \(B(n,q)\). According to the Bernstein inequality [38], for any constant \(\epsilon\in(0,1)\), we have

\[\Pr\left(\left|\sum_{1\leq j\leq n}\bm{1}_{\mathcal{E}_{i}}(j)-nq \right|\geq\epsilon nq\right) \leq 2\exp\left(-\frac{\frac{1}{2}\epsilon^{2}n^{2}q^{2}}{\sum_{1 \leq j\leq n}E\{\bm{1}_{\mathcal{E}_{i}}^{2}(j)\}+\epsilon nq/3}\right)\] \[=2\exp\left(-\frac{\frac{1}{2}\epsilon^{2}n^{2}q^{2}}{nq+\epsilon nq /3}\right)\leq 2\exp\left(-\frac{3}{8}\epsilon^{2}nq\right).\]

The last inequality holds because of \(\epsilon<1\). Therefore,

\[\Pr\left(\mathop{\cup}\limits_{1\leq i\leq n}\left\{|\mathcal{E}_{i}|-nq|\geq \epsilon nq\right\}\right)\leq 2n\exp\left(-\frac{3}{8}\epsilon^{2}nq\right)\leq \frac{2}{n^{2}},\] (25)

where the last inequality holds because we assume that \(\epsilon\geq\frac{\sqrt{8\log n}}{\sqrt{npq}}\). Similarly, we have

\[\Pr\left(\mathop{\cup}\limits_{1\leq i\leq n}\left\{|\mathcal{A}_{i}|-npq|\geq \epsilon npq\right\}\right)\leq 2n\exp\left(-\frac{3}{8}\epsilon^{2}npq\right)\leq \frac{2}{n^{2}},\] (26)

\[\Pr\left(\mathop{\cup}\limits_{1\leq i,j\leq n}\left\{\left|\mathcal{E}_{i} \cap\mathcal{A}_{j}|-npq^{2}\right|\geq\epsilon npq^{2}\right\}\right)\leq 2n^{2 }\exp\left(-\frac{3}{8}\epsilon^{2}npq^{2}\right)\leq\frac{2}{n},\] (27)

and

\[\Pr\left(\mathop{\cup}\limits_{1\leq i,j\leq n}\left\{|\mathcal{A}_{ij}|-np^{ 2}q^{2}|\geq\epsilon np^{2}q^{2}\right\}\right)\leq 2n^{2}\exp\left(-\frac{3}{8} \epsilon^{2}np^{2}q^{2}\right)\leq\frac{2}{n}.\] (28)

Hence, we complete the proof of Lemma 1 once \(n\geq 4\).

### Proof of Proposition 1

We can first compute

\[\sum_{1\leq i,j\leq n}\|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm{X}_{j}\|_{F} \leq\sum_{1\leq i,j\leq n}\frac{1}{|\mathcal{A}_{ij}|}\sum_{k\in \mathcal{A}_{ij}}(\|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm{X}_{k}\|_{F}+\|\bm{X}_{j}-\bm{X}_{k}\|_{F})\] (29) \[\leq\frac{1}{(1-\epsilon)np^{2}q^{2}}\sum_{1\leq i,j\leq n}\sum_{ k\in\mathcal{A}_{ij}}(\|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm{X}_{k}\|_{F}+\|\bm{X}_{j}-\bm{X}_{k}\|_{F}).\]

Here, the first inequality comes from the triangle inequality, while the second one follows from Lemma 1. Now, invoking Lemma 1, which tells \(|\mathcal{A}_{k}|\leq(1+\epsilon)npq\), gives

\[\sum_{1\leq i,j\leq n}\sum_{k\in\mathcal{A}_{ij}}\|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm {X}_{k}\|_{F} =\sum_{1\leq i\leq n}\sum_{k\in\mathcal{A}_{i}}\sum_{j\in\mathcal{A}_{ k}}\|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm{X}_{k}\|_{F}\] \[\leq(1+\epsilon)npq\sum_{1\leq i\leq n}\sum_{k\in\mathcal{A}_{i}} \|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm{X}_{k}\|_{F}\]\[=(1+\epsilon)npq\sum_{(i,k)\in\mathcal{A}}\|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm{X}_{k}\|_{F}.\]

By symmetry, we conclude that

\[\sum_{1\leq i,j\leq n}\sum_{k\in\mathcal{A}_{ij}}(\|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm{X}_{k}\|_{F}+ \|\bm{X}_{j}-\bm{X}_{k}\|_{F})\leq 2(1+\epsilon)npq\sum_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{A}}\|\bm{X}_ {i}-\bm{X}_{j}\|_{F}.\] (30)

Furthermore, we claim the following bound for any \(\bm{X}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)^{n}\):

\[\sum_{1\leq i,j\leq n}\|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm{X}_{j}\|_{F}\geq\frac{n}{2}\operatorname {dist}_{1}(\bm{X},\bm{X}^{\star}).\] (31)

Combining (29), (30), (31), and the fact \(g(\bm{X})=\sum_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{A}}\|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm{X}_{j}\|_{F}\) establishes Proposition 1. Hence, it remains to show (31). First of all, according to the triangle inequality, we have

\[\sum_{1\leq i,j\leq n}\|\bm{X}_{i}-\bm{X}_{j}\|_{F}\geq\sum_{1\leq i\leq n} \left\|n\bm{X}_{i}-\sum_{1\leq j\leq n}\bm{X}_{j}\right\|_{F}=n\sum_{1\leq i \leq n}\|\bm{X}_{i}-\overline{\bm{X}}\|_{F},\] (32)

where \(\overline{\bm{X}}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{1\leq j\leq n}\bm{X}_{j}\) can be taken as a diagonal matrix (since the Frobenius norm is invariant up to a global rotation) with its first \((d-1)\) diagonal entries being positive. Finally, applying the following lemma to (32) provides (31).

**Lemma 7**.: _For any \(\bm{A}\in\mathrm{SO}(d)\) and \(\bm{B}=\text{Diag}(b_{1},\ldots,b_{d})\) satisfying \(b_{1},\ldots,b_{d-1}\in[0,1]\) and \(b_{d}\in[-1,1]\), we have_

\[\|\bm{A}-\bm{B}\|_{F}\geq\frac{1}{2}\|\bm{A}-\bm{I}\|_{F}.\]

